  {:slug "data-002-etl-cdc-to-dim",
   :instruction
   "A company has 5 source databases (Postgres for transactional, MySQL for\nlegacy ERP, MongoDB for product catalog, Snowflake for warehoused\nanalytics, Salesforce for CRM). They need to build a dimensional model\n(star schema) for executive dashboards.\n\nCDC streams from the 5 sources are available via Debezium → Kafka.\nUpdate frequencies vary: transactional ~1K events/min, ERP ~10/min,\ncatalog ~5/min, Snowflake batch every 4 hours, Salesforce ~200/min.\n\nDesign the ETL pipeline:\n- Identify the fact tables and dimension tables (a \"customer orders by\n  product category\" star at minimum)\n- Choose an SCD strategy per dimension (Type 1 vs Type 2 vs Type 6) with\n  reasoning grounded in WHO will query the data + what questions they\n  ask\n- Define the join logic to reconcile customer IDs across sources\n  (Salesforce uses external_id, transactional uses customer_id,\n  legacy ERP uses cust_no — and they aren't always perfectly matched)\n- Handle late-arriving facts (Snowflake batch lags transactional by up to\n  4 hours)\n- Define the freshness SLA for dashboards (real-time? 15-min? hourly?)\n  and justify with consumer needs\n\nReturn:\n- `:fact-tables` + `:dimension-tables` (name, grain, columns, SCD type)\n- `:ingestion-flow` (per-source path through Kafka → transform → load)\n- `:reconciliation-strategy` for customer-ID conflicts\n- `:freshness-sla` + the architectural choices that achieve it\n- `:open-questions` — things you'd need to ask the business before finalizing",
