  {:slug "data-003-optimize-slow-query",
   :instruction
   "A slow query in production:\n\n```sql\nSELECT u.id, u.name, u.email,\n       COUNT(o.id) AS order_count,\n       SUM(o.total_cents) AS lifetime_value\nFROM users u\nLEFT JOIN orders o ON o.user_id = u.id AND o.status = 'completed'\nWHERE u.signup_date >= NOW() - INTERVAL '90 days'\n  AND u.email_verified = TRUE\nGROUP BY u.id, u.name, u.email\nHAVING COUNT(o.id) >= 3\nORDER BY lifetime_value DESC\nLIMIT 100;\n```\n\nTable stats:\n- `users` (12M rows, ~5 GB): indexes on (id PK), (signup_date)\n- `orders` (180M rows, ~80 GB): indexes on (id PK), (user_id),\n  (created_at), (status)\n- The query runs in 14 seconds. Customer-facing dashboard expects <500ms.\n\nDiagnose AND fix. Provide:\n- `:query-plan-analysis` — the most likely bottleneck (sequential scan,\n  bad join order, sort spill, etc.) and the signals that point to it\n- `:proposed-rewrite` — the rewritten SQL with an explanation of each\n  change\n- `:index-recommendations` — exact `CREATE INDEX` statements with the\n  rationale for each (and the storage / write-amplification cost)\n- `:expected-improvement` — your honest estimate of post-fix p95\n- `:verification-plan` — what to measure to confirm the improvement\n  before rolling it out to all dashboards\n- `:risks` — what could regress; consider write amplification, index\n  bloat, planner reliance on stats",
   :source-path
